@C atlas-self-arch-id-convention-intrinsic-limit :: meta [10*]
  question: at what family cardinality does atlas.n6 hit ID grok-cost ceiling?
  measured: distinct_two_token_families = 2188 (already FAR above prompt's 20-30 estimate)
  intrinsic ceiling reached LONG ago — atlas.n6 already operates in the post-ambiguity regime
  evidence:
    1. ID lengths up to 86 chars (p99=65) — names encode semantic path because no registry exists
    2. Hyphens carry 7+ tokens in long IDs — author uses hyphen-as-path delimiter, but no `/` separator means greppers can't distinguish family from variant
    3. 1785 entries share `n6-atlas-*` prefix — first-token grep returns 17.5% of corpus
    4. Date-anchored IDs already in use organically: `...-verified-2026-03-31-...` (16+ instances) — date is mid-string, not anchored, hard to filter
  schema-guard cost:
    regex `^[a-zA-Z0-9_.+-]+$` matches all observed IDs — O(L) where L=mean 24
    NO complexity wall yet on validation; complexity is in HUMAN-grok and consumer-grep, not regex
  cross-cutting consumer cost:
    every grep-by-family probe scales with K (families) × N (entries/family)
    measured: 2188 × ~5 mean = ~10k probes for full family-sweep; tractable but the per-family discrimination is the bottleneck
  convergence:
    atlas.n6 ALREADY past explicit ID-registry threshold
    next-step is NOT more naming convention but a registry-block (`@F atlas-id-registry`) that lists family→prefix→count

@C atlas-self-arch-id-convention-extension-proposals :: meta [10*]
  three highest-value INTRINSIC ID-convention extensions (ranked by leverage / migration cost):

  PROPOSAL 1 — VERSIONED IDs via `.vN` suffix (HIGHEST LEVERAGE, LOWEST MIGRATION COST)
    convention: `clay-iter-50-DEFINITIVE-iter-36-REPRODUCTION.v2` for refined entries
    rationale (intrinsic): atlas.n6 has 187 colliding IDs. Most are intentional re-statement, BUT some clay-iter entries ARE refinements without versioning (clay-iter-13-saturation-tracking AND clay-iter-13-main-axes-termination-met both exist as siblings of clay-iter-12-saturation-tracking, clay-iter-14-15-saturation-tracking-with-recommendation — clearly an evolution chain encoded by adding suffixes)
    beneficiary entries: clay-iter-12/13/14-15-saturation-tracking — these would become clay-iter-saturation-tracking.v1/.v2/.v3 (more grokable than current naming)
    migration cost: ZERO mandatory migration (additive convention, NEW entries opt-in)
    schema-guard delta: extend regex to `[a-zA-Z0-9_.+-]+(\.v[0-9]+)?` — already permissive, no breakage
    convergence-effect: collapses N entries-per-cascade to 1 ID + N versions; cuts authoring ambiguity for the dominant clay-iter family (338 entries)

  PROPOSAL 2 — DATE-ANCHORED suffix `@YYYY-MM-DD` (MEDIUM LEVERAGE, ZERO COLLISION RISK)
    convention: `clay-iter-50-DEFINITIVE@2026-04-28` — date as @-suffix, NOT mid-string hyphen
    rationale (intrinsic): atlas.n6 ALREADY has organic date-anchoring inside IDs (16+ instances of `...-verified-2026-03-31-...`) but it's MID-STRING and unsearchable. `@DATE` suffix is greppable as `@2026-04-28$`
    beneficiary entries: ALL `n6-atlas-*-verified-YYYY-MM-DD-*` entries (the diffusion / LLM survey families, ~30+ entries)
    migration cost: NEW entries only; existing date-mid-string entries left as-is (foundation-axiom invariance respected)
    intrinsic limit: `@` is unused in current atlas.n6 IDs (verified — no `@` in ID space, only as type-tag prefix), so this token is FREE

  PROPOSAL 3 — REGISTRY-BLOCK `@F atlas-id-registry` (HIGH LEVERAGE, ONE-SHOT)
    convention: a single @F block at top of each shard listing family→prefix→count→canonical-form
    example body:
      registry:
        clay-iter: prefix=clay-iter-N-* count=338 canonical=clay-iter-{N}-{descriptor}[.v{V}]
        n6-atlas-bt: prefix=n6-atlas-bt-N-* count=1423 canonical=n6-atlas-bt-{N}-{descriptor}
        disc-blowup: prefix=disc-blowup-* count=728 canonical=disc-blowup-{operator-tower}
    rationale (intrinsic): 2188 distinct families is too many for human grok — past the convergence ceiling. A registry block is atlas.n6's own DSL solution (already uses @F type-tag for facts; this is a fact-about-IDs)
    beneficiary entries: ALL — registry block lets new authors discover existing prefixes before minting collisions
    migration cost: ONE @F block per shard at append time, ~50 lines; existing IDs unchanged
    schema-guard delta: NEW @F type semantics (`@F atlas-id-registry` is a reserved fact-class) — minimal regex change

@R atlas-self-arch-id-convention-foundation-invariance :: rule [10*]
  invariant: existing IDs (n6-master-*, clay-master-*, ouroboros-*, foundation_axiom_*, n6-atlas-*) MUST NOT be renamed under any of the 3 proposals
  enforcement: all 3 proposals are ADDITIVE (suffix-only or new-block) — no mutation of existing ID strings
  verification: foundation_axiom_semantic_ceiling, clay-master-* (8 entries), MILL-V3-M5-ouroboros-v2-namespace-aware all preserved bit-identical

